      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " growth) of peace, the vine, shall give its fruit.\" But there is no especial reason why the vine should be called \"the seed of peace.\" It is not peculiar among fruit trees for requiring a time of peace for its cultivation. And the term \"seed\" is very inappropriate to the vine, which was not raised from seed, but from cuttings and layers. Perowne also points out that such a rendering destroys the balance of the three following clauses, which explain and expand the general statement that agriculture shall prosper. Dr. Alexander takes \"the seed of peace\" to be that from which peace springs; ",
